sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT major_code) 
FROM employment_trends 
WHERE employment_rate < 0.5 AND year > 2020;

external_knowledge:
- 'Agriculture' refers to the industry sector of employment;
- 'Average full-time employment' refers to the average number of graduates employed full-time year-round;
- 'Average employed' refers to the average number of employed graduates per institution.

- Full-time year-round employment typically refers to positions that are both full-time (usually 40 hours per week) and year-round (12 months a year);
- Unemployment rate is the percentage of the labor force that is unemployed and actively seeking employment;
- Median salary is the value separating the higher half from the lower half of a data sample;
- Employment statistics can provide insights into the job market and the value of different majors.

sql:
SELECT employment_rate
FROM employment_trends
WHERE major_code = 0 AND year = 2022;

SELECT AVG(employment_rate) AS average_employment_rate
FROM employment_trends
WHERE major_code = 0 AND year = 2022;

external_knowledge:
- 'Agriculture & Natural Resources' refers to a category of academic majors focused on fields like agriculture, forestry, and environmental management;
- 'Past five years' refers to the most recent five years from the current year;
- 'Average employment rate' is the mean employment rate for the specified category and time period;
- 'Above 50%' indicates that the average employment rate is more than 0.5.

- "Blooming with the highest average salaries and employment rates" refers to majors with high average 75th percentile salaries and employment rates;
- "Consistent growth over the years" refers to institutions with more than 5 trend entries;
- "Latest harvest of 2022" refers to the year 2022.

sql:
SELECT SUM(employed) AS total_employed_graduates
FROM employment_stats
WHERE major_code = 0;

SELECT median
FROM employment_stats
WHERE major_code = 0 AND year = 0 AND institution_id = 0;

external_knowledge:
- "Top 5 majors" refers to the majors with the highest average employment rates;
- "Shining brightly" is a metaphor for having high employment rates;
- "Across all institutions and years" indicates that the data is aggregated over multiple institutions and time periods;
- "Average employment rate" is calculated by taking the mean of employment rates for each major across all institutions and years.

- "Bloomed in the garden of employment" refers to majors with a high employment rate;
- "Shadow of unemployment is less than 5%" means the unemployment rate is less than 0.05;
- "Median salary that averages more than $50,000" means the average median salary is greater than 50,000.

- 'Specified major' refers to the major with `major_code = 0`;
- 'Last decade' refers to the years between 2010 and 2020;
- 'Low unemployment rate' refers to an unemployment rate of 10% or less.

sql:
SELECT total AS number_of_graduates
FROM employment_stats
WHERE major_code = 1 AND year = 1 AND institution_id = 1;

external_knowledge:
- 'Agriculture & Natural Resources' is a category of majors;
- 'public institutions' refers to institutions that are publicly funded;
- 'post-2015' indicates the data is from the year 2016 onwards;
- 'employed graduates' refers to the number of graduates who have found employment after completing their studies.

sql:
SELECT MIN(avg_graduates) AS min_avg_graduates
FROM (
    SELECT major_code, AVG(total) AS avg_graduates
    FROM employment_stats
    GROUP BY major_code
) AS avg_by_major;
